(Prosper Loan Data Exploration)¶

Introduction¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This dataset contains data about Prosper, a Credit Company that facilitates peer-to-peer lending. In this dataset there are 113,937 loans in total, with 81 different variables. I have used the following factors to conduct my investigation: Term, LoanStatus, BorrowerRate, ProsperRating (Alpha), ListingCategory (numeric), EmploymentStatus, DelinquenciesLast7Years, StatedMonthlyIncome, TotalProsperLoans, LoanOriginalAmount, LoanOriginationDate, Recommendations, and Investors, they are also some of the terms used by Prosper.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

After cleaning, there are now 84853 for the Loan dataframe as against 113937 loan listings on Prosper, a peer-to-peer credit company. LoanStatus, BorrowerRate, ProsperRating (Alpha), ListingCategory (numeric), EmploymentStatus, DelinquenciesLast7Years, StatedMonthlyIncome, TotalProsperLoans, LoanOriginalAmount, LoanOriginationDate, Recommendations, Investors are the variables. The majority of the variables are numeric, though there are a few that categorical:

  • LoanStatus - categorical variable
  • ProsperRating (Aplha) ordinal categorical variable with the following values from higher to lower ('AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'HR')
  • EmploymentStatus - categorical variable
  • ListingCategory (numeric) - a numeric code for category of credit (will explored in detail below).
  • LoanOriginationDate - datetime object

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I would want to know what feature(s) are used to predict a default on credit.

I would want to check what are the major factors that are connected with prosper credit rating.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I hope that The Prosper rating will have the biggest impact on the chances of a loan default. This might depend on the borrower's income and employment status.

Because ProsperRating (Alpha) is ordinal categorial variable (From the highest rating A to the lowest HR) We need to convert it using pandas:

In [149]:
plt.figure(figsize = [10, 7])
ordinal_list = ['AA', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'HR']


ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_list)
loan['ProsperRating (Alpha)'] = loan['ProsperRating (Alpha)'].astype(ordered_var)

#then:
sb.countplot(data=loan, x='ProsperRating (Alpha)', color=color);

The ratings are relatively evenly divided, with the highest AA and lowest HR ratings being the least prevalent and the average rating C being the most common.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of Prosper ratings is roughly normally distributed. Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The vast majority of loans are current ones. We are not interested in any current loans (or loans with a specified past due time), and chargedoff loans can be regarded defaulted because our major purpose is to define driving elements of loan outcome. In [161]:
# leaving only completed chargedoff or defaulted listings
condition = (loan['LoanStatus'] == 'Completed') | (loan['LoanStatus'] == 'Defaulted') | (loan['LoanStatus'] == 'Chargedoff')
loan = loan[condition]

# setting chargedoff as defaulted
def change_to_defaulted(row):
    if row['LoanStatus'] == 'Chargedoff':
        return 'Defaulted'
    else:
        return row['LoanStatus']
#then
loan['LoanStatus'] = loan.apply(change_to_defaulted, axis=1)
#Check the values counts again
loan['LoanStatus'].value_counts()
Out[161]:
Completed    19664
Defaulted     6341
Name: LoanStatus, dtype: int64

We now have 19664 completed loans and 6341 defaulted loans.

Because ListingCategory (numeric) is set up as numeric and most of the values have a very low frequency, we need modify it to categorical and reduce the number of categories for easier visualisation:

In [162]:
# helper function:
categories = {1: 'Debt Consolidation', 2: 'Home Improvement', 3: 'Business', 6: 'Auto', 7: 'Other'}
def reduce_categories(row):
    loan_category = row['ListingCategory (numeric)']
    if  loan_category in categories:
        return categories[loan_category]
    else:
        return categories[7]

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Individuals with poorer credit ratings are more likely to receive default credits, as expected. The categories of business and home improvement appear to be more risky. For defaulted credits, the borrower rate is usually higher. Credits with a 60-month maturity are riskier than those with a shorter maturity (12 months). Individuals with a bad credit rating have a higher rate of borrowing. A better rating is associated with a larger monthly revenue. Individuals with lower ratings are more likely to be unemployed, self-employed, retired, or working part-time.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

One notable observation I've made is that the prosper rating D is the most common among defaulted credits.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Our first impressions were confirmed. Credit outcome is determined by Prosper rating, Term, and Employment status. For all ratings save the lowest, defaulted credits are larger than completed credits. Other and business categories are more prone to default in terms of credit purposes (business category also tend to have larger loans). Long-term (60-month) loans are riskier than mid-term (36-month) and short-term (24-month) loans.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It was discovered that defaulted credits for people with high Prosper ratings are typically larger than fulfilled credits. Another intriguing finding is that people with the lowest rating (HR) only have mid-term (36-month) credits.
